<h2>How to Know If an Update Hit Your Site</h2>
<p>Not every traffic fluctuation is an algorithm update. Here is how to diagnose the cause.</p>
<h3>Step 1: Check the Timeline</h3>
<p>Compare your traffic drop against <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/updates/ranking">Google's Search Status Dashboard</a>. If your drop aligns with a confirmed update date (within 2-3 days), the update likely caused it.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Analyze the Scope</h3>
<p>Open Google Search Console. Look at which pages lost impressions and clicks.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Sitewide drop</strong> = Core update likely reassessed your overall quality</li>
<li><strong>Specific pages dropped</strong> = Those pages may not meet current quality standards</li>
<li><strong>Specific queries dropped</strong> = Google may have changed how it interprets those searches</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Compare Against Competitors</h3>
<p>If your competitors gained what you lost, study their content. What do their pages have that yours do not? More depth? Better expertise signals? Fresher data?</p>
<h3>Step 4: Wait Before Reacting</h3>
<p>Core updates take 1-3 weeks to fully roll out. Rankings fluctuate during rollout. Wait until Google confirms the update is complete before analyzing results. Reacting too early leads to changes that make things worse.</p>
